<td></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>O5-09</td>
<td>O5-07</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>O5-10</td>
<td>O5-08</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>O5-12</td>
<td>O5-11</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><strong>O5-01:</strong> With deadlock, the motion is tabled until O5-13 is available to cast their vote. If there is no other business-</p>
<p><strong>Administrator:</strong> The Charter states that in the event of a deadlock, I may cast the deciding vote.</p>
<p><strong>O5-01:</strong> Yes sir. I didn't think that you-</p>
<p><strong>Administrator:</strong> <em>[Interrupting]</em> Just because I decline to vote more often than not doesn't mean that I don't keep myself informed, One. Twelve, you have faith in Dr. Low's assessment. I have faith in you. However, Eight raises a good point. I'm not willing to dump unlimited funds into this <em>Kelipat Nogah</em> Initiative of hers without assurances that it'll pan out.</p>
<p><strong>O5-12:</strong> Oh, I understand that, sir. I assure you that-</p>
<p><strong>Administrator:</strong> <em>[Interrupting]</em> To that end, I will authorize a paired-down version of what Dr. Low has proposed, and I'm making you Overwatch over the entire project. If this turns out to be a pipe-dream as Eight is convinced it will be, it will cost you your seat on this council. Is that clear?</p>
<p><strong>O5-12:</strong> Yes, sir.</p>
